element.documentation:
"This way of working is proned to error and we spend excess admin time in the back office administrating this task.
The risk for the project is that the mistake in the back office affects timings of rotations where people arrive too late or too early, so we have unwanted overlaps or gaps which could also affect our utilisation rate negatively. "

"We rely on keeping track of people's past project records manually and/or we rely on Team Leads in the back office to remember. This is a vulnerable setup and it can affect us negatively because we would risk allocating a person to a project who might not be the best fit for a certain task. Today, we are at risk of being incompliant with GDPR as we keep track of this information manually and not storing the information in the most optimal way."

"The effect is that it disturbs the utilisation rate in a negative way by having booked someone who is no longer required or if the project has moved ahead in time, then the risk is that the department does not have time to prepare the resources according to project request.
It complicates our ability to document details in a request to ensure we do not rely on certain people's memory and also our ability to settle on internal lessons learned and who should have done what differently (tracking MoM, change requests, actions, decisions as part of a log) Sometimes, we have also seen arguments on settling on who should cover certain costs."

"The effect is that the department spends a lot of admin time to retrieve the info as well as there is a risk of mistakes by missing key project-related information ultimately affecting how well projects are staffed.
There is a risk we send people to site who are not allowed to work because of missing or incorrect certificates. Also, there is no clear process on how we get information about project specific requirements to training or other certificates/paperwork."
"Employment terms may be remembered by line managers and planners or P&C can be asked via a ticket. There is a risk we plan a work pattern that is non compliant with the employees contract. "

The back office either assumes everything is up to date or it must be checked with Line Manager or Training coordinator which takes extra time to search and retrieve information in various systems. We risk sending people out to work without mandatory trainings in place.

"It takes time to transfer the completed scenario into the live plan. There is also a risk that the live plan has been changed by a colleague in the meantime so data could end up being wrong or misaligned.
While working on the possible scenarios it is ideal to ""lock"" the involved employees in the live plan. This has to be done with a note or in the actual timeline which also takes time."

"The quality of the budget inputs we can provide is poor because we often find incorrect or old information across these different ""dead"" sources which we use to base our assumptions and business case on. The risk of human error is also highly likely because we scan across multiple docments that are all manually updated and filled with ""dead data"".
Construction management then receives and approves budget requests which turn out not to represent reality meaning we end up having too few or too many headcounts in our request. This ultimately affects our ability to staff projects appropriately or it is affecting our utilisation rate in a negative way.
The admin time we spend in the back office is also excessive which is even more dissatisfying as the quality of the output is often poor."

"This is time-consuming task for back office to continously update the two sheets; first updating one and then reflecting the changes in the second file. We do this on a continous basis (weekly). There is also a human error factor with having to rely on remembering to reflect changes across two sheets or somebody unintendedly messing up formulas that disturb calculating functionalities"

"This takes a lot of admin time, and since we don't have a clever way of communicating about our ability to support elsewhere in the organisation, it is only by chance if we manage to sell them meaning we miss out on optimising our utilisation rates.
The pain point is also that it is a manual task to call stakeholders to try and sell resources, and checking up on resource's skill levels to find out if they could meet the requirements from the requesting part within Vestas (i.e. Manufacturing or Service). "

"The pain point is that threre are too many manually supported tasks for back office to process becuase systems are not inter-linked (i.e. SAP / VSP / SuccessFactors / general ressource plans / site ressource plans showing what happens on a daily basis (i.e. sickness).
Plus the time-consuming aspect is also the human error aspect where we are at risk of our plans/overviews not being 100% accurate which can have a knock-on effect on projects ultimately."

"Pain points are that our Excel sheet does not provide sufficient filtering options to create a useful overview. Moreover, we need to pull data from a number of different systems to collect and share all needed supporting documentation on the allocated resources. "

Pain points are that the planners in the back office maintain our excel sheets, so we are at risk of human error resulting in the risk of sharing incorrect or outdated information to employees on their assignments, and also the fact that we sometimes share more information with a pool of people than we should with respect to being GDPR compliant.

The pain point is that the back office and the personnel allocated to site need to manually provide these data/information - either by e-mail or on a USB stick. This is a time-consuming task and can sometimes delay site inductions and spped in getting ready to access site to start working, but it also conflicts with GDPR when certificates and Next of Kin-informatio nis sent back and forth via e-mail.

The pain point is that this is information is then sitting in these MS Forms related to the survey responses and the feedback shared verbally is stored on our Team Leads' laptops in OneNote. That leaves us vulnearable in terms of accessing and sharing information.

The risk is that the same person (or a group of people) could be allocated to multiple projects at the same time, because poor filtering options mean we could miss out on a person being booked for multiple projects. Ultimately, it affects our ability to execute projects effectively

It is a high risk as it is the only place we have our onshore plans, so we risk missing our already planned activities and project allocations. This affects efficiency in the back office and ultimately affecting projects if errors lead to inappropriate staffing of projects

"The pain point is that when we want to filter on certain data (companies, roles, projects), then we risk not getting the correct result when we have to plan, do changes, make decisions etc. This again affects the efficiency and quality of work in the back office with a knock-on effect on the staffing of projects."

Only internal employees are given access and back office is spending time on creating weekly reports for external supplier, so they cannot see information on who is working where and in which other companies, which projects competitors might have etc.
The risk is that the masterplan is not showing the correct availability, so we cannot make alternative plans in due time which affects the utilisation rate and project staffing quality
We risk sending people on site without the needed certificates or at a wrong date/time. This then affects project efficiency

"If an employee is allocated to a long project there is a risk we do not notice that his certificates run out in the middle of the project, which means we could be facing a safety and compliance issue. When we find out too late, the project would have to deal with less resources for a period of time affecting the efficiency of the project."

Maintaining people's profiles with updated documentation on training certification is at risk of being incorrect ultimately affecting project staffing because dates/info from training course has to be manually entered into SuccessFactor but also that we cannot always document a person's training records correctly for a project causing a safety/compliance issue

"Team Leads in back office have to translate these figures into their own ressource forecast to understand which type of roles, amount of resources, training needs, experience needed (on WTG types), rotation patterns and country-specific legislation will be affecting future resource needs. Team Leads also have to guesstimate on the amount of people needed as these details do not appear for every project. We can do so with an acceptable hit rate, but the knowledge is inside people's heads, so we are vulnerable.
Becuase it is all manually inserted into Excel, we cannot play around with different scenarios to understand how many months we will be over- or udner-staffed and potentially be proactive to ensure more resources in due time that are qualified and properly trianed."

"We are ""left in the dark"" with no data, so we are unable to analyse on past, current and future performance. It affects our ability to forecast properly and it leaves us with periods where we are under- or over-staffed, and we find out too late because the system has not warned us or provided us with data to anaylyse on so we could have miitigated in due time.
It also leaves us in a vulnerable position towards external providers and working with our internal colleagues who are responsible for sourcing external resources / labour hire agreements. We have no data to argue on utilisation rates according to certain sourcing strategies/agreements. We cannot see in due time if we might be in need of more resources and maybe more suppliers, so it leaves us with little time to prepare if we come too late in the process and ask for more external resources. Then we end up taking the ""best of the worst"" because of time pressure."

The pain points are that the roles on site cannot access a system to obtain these types of information which could be relevant for a Marine Coordinator or a Project Supervisor who needs to prepare resources in i.e. SeaPlanner (system). We then have to send something by mail, or allocated personnel may have to keep documents/certificates on USB sticks.
Pain point here is that this is time consuming and manual process. Human factor also in play if correct options are not selected resulting in an obscured view due to wrong inputs

Having to go through a full resource plan to check if holiday allowances have been taken or not. Sickness is not completely tracked, tickets do not get responded to. Managers/HR/Payroll not on the same page as information is broken down or not available.One system that accounts for holidays/sickness where the values for each country are pre loaded to each employee (contract dependant UK/DK/DE) When holidays are booked they are deducted from each persons allowance and payroll are informed. Sickness is the same and HR are informed in these cases. With a mobile view of this information (mentioned in another point in the use case) People can see their own holiday enttlements and payroll are up to date with this info. Sickness is then properly tracked according to country specific rules.

"Pain point here is excess time consumption and manual work for both the person taking time off and the planners in the back office. Second, the planners in the back office are sometimes deprived from the opportunity to reject the time slot that the resource has proposed to participate in training because the suggested time slot could conflict with other agreements entered between back office and construction projects.
There is also the human error factor that can come into play if someone forgets to update or inform back office then this important info is missed from the live plan and ultimately this can have an effect of the staffing of projects."
